Remember that a limit describes the y-values of a graph \textbf{around},
but not \textbf{at} the x-value, whereas $f(x)$ gives the y-value of a
graph \textbf{at} \emph{x}.

So drawing a picture where $\lim_{x \to 1} f(x)$ (y-values are equal to
2 near \emph{x = 1}) could look like this:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_2c_example2.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 2c example2.jpg}
\end{figure}

But, $f(1)$, the y-value at \emph{x = 1}, could be equal to something
else, like 1:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_2c_example1.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 2c example1.jpg}
\end{figure}

Because the conclusion of the statement is not necessarily true, the
statement is false.
